      "type": "narration",
      "content": "The air in the Gilded Anchor tastes of brine and roasted cumin, thick enough to chew. Below the wrought-iron balcony, the Lucian Arsenal claws at the sky, its cranes and drydocks a forest of rusted iron and fresh timber where the bones of the old Imperial naval base still protrude from the harbor mud. Sunlight glints off the domed roof of the Basilica of the Navigator Stars, sending sharp reflections dancing across the water, while the distant, perpetual glow of the Civic Flame bathes the upper city in a warm, artificial haze. The roar of the port rises up—shouts of stevedores, the creak of rope, the guttural bark of Elaphine traders haggling over crates of exotic timber—but here, among the silk hangings and polished bronze of the private salon, the noise is a muffled, rhythmic thrum.\n\nValerius, a councilman whose velvet doublet strains over a solid frame, paces the imported Zhiran rug with a glass of dark wine held loosely in one hand. Opposite him, an Elaphine merchant named Hestus stands motionless, his coat a sleek map of greys and browns, antlers scraping the plaster ceiling as he shifts his weight. A ledger lies open between them on the table, pages fluttering in the draft from the balcony doors. Valerius stops pacing and sets the glass down with a sharp *clink* that cuts through the ambient noise. He leans forward, both hands planting on the table's surface, knuckles pale.\n\n\"The Doge doesn't care about the spice tariffs, Hestus,\" Valerius says, his voice low and rough like ground stones. \"He cares about what came off the *Star of Antheion* last night. The manifest says silk. The manifest lies.\" Hestus doesn't blink, his large, dark eyes reflecting the flicker of the wall sconce. The Elaphine reaches into the deep pocket of his coat, the fabric rustling, and withdraws a small, lead-lined box. He places it on the ledger with a heavy thud. The box is scratched, the corners worn smooth by many hands, but the seal impressed into the lead is unmistakable—a sun broken by a lightning bolt, the sigil of the Empire that shouldn't exist anymore. Valerius stares at the seal, his breath catching audibly, before he slowly lifts his head and fixes his bloodshot eyes on the figure standing in the corner of the room.",
