    {
      "id": "0b7c9ae3-f32e-495b-bc2a-111693ebffed",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Magic and the Body**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Magic and the Body**\n\nThough magi do not understand *why*, magic is intrinsically tied to what the Aegis call \"DNA\"—the fundamental code written into every cell of a living being. When a healer mends a wound, the magic recognizes and restores only tissue belonging to that specific individual. Foreign matter—bacteria, parasites, even another person's blood—is invisible to healing magic at best, or treated as an invader at worst.\n\nThis has several implications:\n\n**Illness:** Healing magic cannot cure disease. A healer can mend the damage illness causes—closing lesions, reducing inflammation, strengthening weakened tissue—but the infection itself must be fought by the body's natural defenses or treated through herbal medicine. Plagues still ravage populations; healers can only ease suffering and buy time.\n\n**Aging and Cancer:** The body's own cells gradually accumulate errors over a lifetime. Healing magic cannot distinguish between \"correct\" and \"corrupted\" self—tumorous growths and aged tissue both register as belonging to the person. Thus, even the most powerful healers cannot grant immortality or cure cancers. Some theorize this is why Passion burns so hot: the SOUL knows the body is always failing.\n\n**Sympathetic Magic:** A lock of hair, a vial of blood, a shed fingernail—these carry the same signature that healing magic recognizes. Curses and bindings using such materials can target a specific individual with terrible precision. This is why many cultures have strict taboos around disposing of bodily materials, and why powerful individuals employ servants specifically to burn their hair clippings and nail trimmings.\n\n**The Blood Prohibition:** Across nearly all healing traditions, transferring blood between individuals is strictly forbidden. Early attempts to save the dying through blood transfusion resulted in catastrophe—healing magic performed afterward would attack the foreign blood, cause uncontrollable clotting, or simply fail entirely. Temples teach that \"the blood is the soul's vessel; to mix blood is to fracture the self.\" The few who have received transfusions can never again benefit from magical healing, a fate considered worse than death in many cultures.\n\n**The Aegis Understanding:** From their lunar exile, the Aegis long ago deduced the mechanism underlying these phenomena. They know that sufficient radiation scrambles this biological code, disrupting magical ability entirely. Weapons designed on this principle exist in Aegis archives—elegant, effective, utterly useless while they remain trapped on the moon, unable to act against the humans they were forbidden to harm.",
