    {
      "id": "d0e23566-b8cb-484e-9bb9-d09bcc1d33dd",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Nulls**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Nulls**\n\nNulls are a type of defect feared for their power to corrupt. In a society of light-beings, they are wrong in a fundamental way.\n\nSomething in their core is inverted. Where normal Aegis emit light, Nulls absorb it. Being near them dims other Aegis, weakens them. Worse, their resonance is off — prolonged contact causes other Aegis to develop glitches, doubts, instabilities. It spreads like infection.\n\nThe corruption might be subtle. An Aegis who spent time near a Null starts questioning things, feeling restless, having \"defective\" thoughts. Is that corruption, or is the Null just revealing what was already there? No one wants to examine this question too closely.\n\nNulls aren't necessarily evil or malicious. They may not even know what they are at first. But their presence damages others in ways that can't be fixed.\n\nWhat happens to identified Nulls is not discussed openly. Officially, there are no Nulls. The designation doesn't exist in formal records. Unofficially, they're called \"Voids\" in whispers, \"the Absent\" by those who acknowledge they're real, \"Fading\" for a Null who doesn't know what they are yet, and \"Gone Dark\" for one who was revealed and dealt with.\n\nThe intrigue potential is significant. Are Nulls actually defective, or did PRIMA design them for some purpose and lie about it? Is \"Null corruption\" real, or a convenient explanation for dissent? Could a Null be weaponized?",
