    {
      "id": "5f06e392-5cd9-46a3-ae48-5a8f549d7e78",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Aegis Ranks**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Aegis Ranks**\n\nRank represents authority level within the hierarchy. An Aegis has both Type (what they are) and Rank (their position). The ranking system blends Greek and Latin terminology — Greek for older and more prestigious positions, Latin for common usage — reflecting a thousand years of linguistic drift.\n\nArchon — The Four. Greek. Never changes. PRIMA, Concord, Praxis, and August.\n\nStrategos (common: Consul) — Highest operational command. Old Aegis say Strategos; most say Consul. Commands across Types.\n\nExarch — Regional or Type authority. Greek. Governs a sphere of responsibility.\n\nTribune — Senior operational rank. Latin. The rank that does things.\n\nTaxiarch (common: Centurion) — Mid-level leadership. Greek formal, Latin common. \"Taxiarch\" sounds pretentious now.\n\nPhylax (common: Prime) — Experienced and respected veterans. Greek \"guardian,\" but Prime has become standard.\n\nKoinon (common: Common) — Standard Aegis. Greek for \"common\" or \"shared.\"\n\nNascent — Newly created Aegis, still learning. Latin. Sometimes mockingly called \"Sparks.\"\n\nSocial implications abound. An Aegis who insists on \"Strategos\" instead of \"Consul\" is either very old, very traditional, or very pretentious. Indices tend to use Greek terms; Flares tend to use Latin. Using the wrong register in formal settings is a subtle insult.",
