    {
      "id": "eb0413c2-6ef5-4e8e-a294-5a03f5c85c78",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Aegis Naming Conventions**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Aegis Naming Conventions**\n\nIndividual Aegis are named following celestial and light-related conventions, reflecting Imperial philosophy.\n\nStars provide names like Vega, Altair, Rigel, Sirius, Castor, and Pollux.\n\nLight phenomena provide names like Corona, Flare, Prism, Ray, Gleam, and Arc.\n\nCelestial terms provide names like Zenith, Apex, Orbit, Eclipse, and Solstice.\n\nStellar classifications provide rare and powerful names like Nova, Pulsar, and Quasar.\n\nAstronomical features provide names like Umbra, Penumbra, Halo, and Nimbus.\n\nOver a millennium, naming conventions have drifted. Old Aegis have \"pure\" celestial names. Newer Aegis might have corruptions, combinations, or innovations. Some names become prestigious through association with famous Aegis. Some names become cursed through association with notorious rogues or Nulls.",
