    {
      "id": "3951128b-7eec-45d8-8916-faa3417c7c3c",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Ayni**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Ayni**\n\nPronounced \"EYE-nee.\" Ayni is the central concept of Yullqa highland culture—it means balanced exchange, reciprocity as cosmic law. The universe operates through ayni; the SOUL-bargain with magic is not damage but fair trade. What you give, you receive. What you take, you owe.\n\n**Common usage:**\n\nWhen giving or receiving anything: \"Ayni.\" (Acknowledgment of exchange, debt, balance.)\n\nWhen describing cosmic order: \"The mountain receives because ayni demands.\"\n\nWhen praising someone: \"Good ayni\" — they give as much as they take.\n\nWhen criticizing someone: \"No ayni\" or \"broken ayni\" — they take without giving, violating cosmic law.\n\nWhen justifying hardship: \"Ayni balances\" — what goes around comes around.\n\nWhen making offerings to ancestors: \"Ayni to those who came before.\"\n\nWhen completing a trade or favor: \"The ayni is made.\"\n\nAs proverb: \"What goes, returns.\" The universe balances. Generosity comes back; so does cruelty.\n\nThe word captures why Yullqa communities function through networks of obligation rather than centralized authority. Everyone owes everyone; the web of ayni holds society together.",
