    {
      "id": "c2088c8e-6855-4415-aa80-8aeaf0daadcb",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Shùn**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Shùn**\n\nPronounced \"shwun\" (falling tone). Shùn is the central concept of Heliushuo philosophy—it means accord, alignment, moving-with. To be shùn is to have found your place in the current and to move with it rather than against it. It's both a state of being and an action—you can \"be shùn\" or you can \"shùn\" something (align yourself with it, accept it, move in harmony with it).\n\n**Common usage:**\n\nWhen accepting news, good or bad: \"Shùn.\" (I receive this; I align with this reality.)\n\nWhen advising someone struggling: \"Find shùn.\" (Stop fighting the current.)\n\nWhen praising someone well-adapted: \"Very shùn.\" (They've found their place.)\n\nWhen criticizing someone: \"No shùn\" or \"un-shùn.\" (They're fighting the natural order, creating disharmony.)\n\nWhen describing a good decision: \"That's shùn.\" (It accords with how things should be.)\n\nWhen something feels wrong: \"Where's the shùn in this?\" (How does this align with proper order?)\n\nAt death: \"They return to shùn.\" (Rejoining the great confluence, perfectly aligned at last.)\n\nThe opposite state—fighting the current, refusing your place, creating disharmony—is called \"nì\" (against, contrary).",
