    {
      "id": "611d4120-2b86-4dd2-91f9-e405ef2ffa27",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Jeongyeol**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Jeongyeol**\n\nJeongyeol (Harmonious Passion) is Goryun's philosophical tradition, a synthesis that validates human nature while maintaining discipline.\n\nThe core concept holds that Passion provides fire; discipline provides the container. Alone, fire destroys. Contained, fire forges. A human who masters both exceeds what single-nature beings achieve — not because humans are superior, but because they have learned to work with their nature rather than against it.\n\nKey tenets include: Passion is not weakness — Zhiran's orthodox view treats Passion as dangerous, but Goryun says Passion itself contains the seeds of discipline. The Forge Metaphor holds that a sword is made through fire and hammer, heat and control, and a human soul is the same. Cultivation through commitment recognizes that humans cultivate best through dedicated pursuit. Balance from within argues that humans can achieve internal harmony without needing beastfolk to complete them.\n\nZhiran scholars find Jeongyeol uncomfortable, as it suggests humans do not need beastfolk to achieve harmony. Goryun scholars respond that they do not claim superiority, only difference.",
