    {
      "id": "81ff1e47-35eb-42f7-ad3f-2d66fc148050",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Dallyeom**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Dallyeom**\n\nPronounced \"dahl-LYUHM.\" Dallyeom is the central concept of Jeongyeol philosophy—it means something like \"forge-heart\" or \"tempered spirit,\" the state of having unified passion and discipline into something stronger than either alone. It's what the Hwarang cultivate, what every Goryun aspires to. Not suppression of fire, not wild burning, but the transformation that happens when heat meets intention.\n\n**Common usage:**\n\nWhen encouraging someone: \"Find your dallyeom.\" (Bring your fire under control; become the blade.)\n\nWhen praising mastery: \"True dallyeom.\" (You've achieved the unity.)\n\nWhen someone loses control: \"Dallyeom broke.\" (The container failed; fire escaped.)\n\nWhen someone is too cold, too controlled: \"Where's the dallyeom?\" (You've lost the fire entirely; you're just cold iron.)\n\nWhen undertaking something difficult: \"Dallyeom will see me through.\"\n\nAs a toast or battle-cry: \"Dallyeom\\!\" (We are forged; we are ready.)\n\nWhen assessing someone: \"Good dallyeom\" or \"weak dallyeom.\"\n\nThe word contains the entire philosophy—humans don't need beastfolk to complete them because they can complete themselves through this internal alchemy.",
