    {
      "id": "7fba79be-19b5-4e95-b307-7654f6218d56",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Kagami**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Kagami**\n\nPronounced \"kah-GAH-mee.\" Kagami is the central concept of Aohane spirituality—it means something like \"true-display\" or \"heaven-reflection,\" the act of showing your genuine self, your gifts, your beauty, in a way that honors the divine. To have kagami is to be authentic, visible, radiant with what you truly are. Hiding your gifts is a failure of kagami; false display is a corruption of kagami.\n\n**Common usage:**\n\nWhen greeting: \"Bright kagami.\" (Your display honors us.)\n\nWhen blessing: \"May your kagami shine.\"\n\nWhen praising: \"True kagami.\" (You're showing your real self beautifully.)\n\nWhen criticizing: \"False kagami\" (you're performing something you're not) or \"hidden kagami\" (you're concealing what you should display).\n\nDuring molting: \"The kagami renews.\" (Your true self is being remade.)\n\nAt death: \"Their kagami returns to heaven.\" (The display is complete; the light goes home.)\n\nWhen encouraging: \"Show your kagami.\" (Don't hide; be seen; be glorious.)\n\nAs philosophy: \"Kagami is truth.\" (What you display is what you are; authenticity is virtue.)\n\nThe Pavonines find mammal cultures baffling because they seem to value concealment, modesty, hiding. To a Pavonine, that's spiritual cowardice—failure of kagami.",
