    {
      "id": "a722a367-5077-4f20-8ad5-dd662eff3533",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**The Old Law**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**The Old Law**\n\nThe beastfolk of the outer reaches believe the land itself has a SOUL — not metaphorically, but literally. Every hill, river, and forest is inhabited by spirits that are the accumulated SOULs of those who died there across millennia. The land remembers. The land judges.\n\nTheir magic is geomantic — it flows through the land's memory, channeled by those who know how to listen. Sacred sites where SOULs concentrate become places of power. Druids do not cast spells so much as negotiate with the accumulated dead.\n\nThis creates a fundamentally different relationship with territory than the mobile Lupines of Göran or the mountain-bound Felines of Drakhar. The beastfolk here cannot leave. Their ancestors are here. To abandon sacred ground is to abandon your dead.",
