    {
      "id": "369dce8d-570c-4a24-b4db-4bcdc208d306",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Gwraidd**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Gwraidd**\n\nPronounced \"GWRY-th\" (the \"dd\" is a voiced \"th\" like in \"the\"). Gwraidd is the central concept of Old Law spirituality—it means root, source, connection-to-soil, ancestry, belonging. Your gwraidd is your link to the land where your ancestors are buried. To have gwraidd somewhere is to belong there in the deepest possible way—your dead are in that earth, and you will join them.\n\n**Common usage:**\n\nWhen asserting belonging: \"My gwraidd is here.\" (My ancestors are in this soil; I am of this place.)\n\nWhen questioning someone's right to speak on local matters: \"Where is your gwraidd?\" (What land holds your dead? What gives you standing?)\n\nWhen blessing: \"Deep gwraidd.\" (May your roots be strong; may your ancestors support you.)\n\nWhen insulting humans: \"No gwraidd.\" (Rootless, newcomers, their dead are elsewhere or nowhere.)\n\nWhen describing sacred sites: \"Old gwraidd.\" (Many generations of dead; deep power.)\n\nAt death: \"They join the gwraidd.\" (They become part of the root-system that supports the living.)\n\nWhen land is desecrated: \"The gwraidd is wounded.\"\n\nWhen defending territory: \"Gwraidd-sworn.\" (Bound by the ancestors in this soil to protect it.)\n\nThe word captures why the beastfolk can't simply leave, can't migrate, can't accept human settlement. This isn't just land—it's where their gwraidd goes down into the earth. Leaving is amputation.",
