    {
      "id": "ed134f3b-0570-4843-9b59-65c409b85b56",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**The Civic Flame**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**The Civic Flame**\n\nThe dominant philosophy of the Thalassic humans centers on the Hearth Flame — every city maintains a sacred fire that represents the collective SOUL of its citizens. But the Civic Flame is more than philosophy. It is infrastructure, weapon, and religion fused into one.\n\n**The Mana Tax**\n\nEvery citizen contributes a tiny portion of their SOUL regularly. Not enough to hurt, not enough to notice — like a tithe paid in exhaustion rather than coin. This contribution happens passively by living within the city's resonance, though temples formalize it with small rituals.\n\nIn return, the Flame provides: walls that do not crack, water that purifies itself, disease that spreads slower, eternal flames at intersections that need no fuel, wards that make enemies uneasy. This is why Thalassic cities *work* — why dense urban living is sustainable, why their streets are clean while the land outside remains medieval.\n\nNon-citizens (foreigners, slaves, resident beastfolk) benefit from this infrastructure but cannot contribute to the Flame. This creates the two-tiered society central to Thalassic culture. Citizenship is not merely legal status — it is spiritual participation.\n\n**The Number**\n\nA Flame requires exactly 347 citizens to kindle and sustain.\n\nNot 350. Not 300. *347*.\n\nTheologians have argued about this for a thousand years. Why this number? What does it symbolize? The truth, known to no one, is that it's arbitrary — the first humans to kindle a Flame happened to have 347 survivors, and the technique calcified. But belief has made it cosmic law.\n\nCities obsessively track citizen counts. Plagues that drop the number below 347 are existential crises. The ruins dotting the Tieravel coast include places where 346 people tried to kindle a Flame and failed.\n\n**The Scream**\n\nWhen a city is truly threatened, the Flame can be unleashed. This requires the Gathering (citizens assembling around the Hearth), the Meditation (hours of synchronized focus), the Feeding (voluntary SOUL-sacrifice beyond the normal tax — this *hurts*), and finally the Release.\n\nFirst, silence. Unnatural silence — sound pulled inward toward the Hearth.\n\nThen implosion. Air pressure drops. Ears pop. Every streetlight in the city gutters and dies as everything feeds the center.\n\nA moment of absolute darkness.\n\nThen the **metallic scream** — not human, not animal. The voice of a thousand souls crying through bronze and iron and stone. The Flame becomes a pillar of light that *reaches*, and whatever it touches is destroyed.\n\n**The Cost**\n\nThe Flame is not the limit — human endurance is. A small Scream leaves hundreds bedridden for days. A full Scream kills dozens of elderly and infirm outright. Sustained defense — multiple Screams — starts killing the population in meaningful numbers. Cities have survived sieges only to collapse afterward, their people too broken to rebuild.\n\nThis creates terrible wartime calculus. Fire early and risk having nothing left for the real assault. Wait too long and lose the outer districts. Every Scream is paid for in the lives of grandparents, the sick, the weak.\n\n**Age and Power**\n\nFlames grow stronger with age. A newly kindled Flame can barely ward its walls. A century-old Flame can break a siege. A millennium-old Flame like Antheion's — no one has tested its limits. The knowledge that it *could* fire at full power is enough.\n\nThis is why old cities are nearly impregnable and new colonies desperately vulnerable. Founding a colony means decades of weakness before the Flame matures. Losing a Flame means starting over with nothing.\n\nThe dark side: this creates intense pressure toward conformity. Those who reject the city — exiles, heretics, the stateless — are spiritually diminished, cut off from communal resonance. Dissent weakens the Flame. Individualism is dangerous. The collective must hold.",
