    {
      "id": "bb36eb96-3911-4d4b-872e-bd44824dc9d8",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Koinon**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Koinon**\n\nPronounced \"KOY-non.\" Koinon is the central concept of Civic Flame spirituality—it means the shared fire, the collective warmth, the thing that makes a city more than just people living near each other. Your koinon is your participation in the civic flame, your contribution and connection to the resonance that makes the city work. To be part of koinon is to be a citizen in the deepest sense—spiritually woven into the collective.\n\n**Common usage:**\n\nWhen affirming unity: \"Koinon.\" (We are one fire; we are together in this.)\n\nWhen greeting fellow citizens: \"Koinon, friend.\"\n\nWhen thanking: \"You strengthen the koinon.\" (Your contribution enriches us all.)\n\nWhen criticizing selfishness: \"No koinon in that.\" (That action doesn't serve the collective; that's cold behavior.)\n\nWhen describing exiles: \"Lost to koinon.\" (Cut off from the shared fire; diminished.)\n\nAt festivals: \"The koinon burns bright\\!\" (We are united; we are powerful together.)\n\nWhen dying well: \"Their koinon endures.\" (Their spark rejoins the collective; they're part of us forever.)\n\nWhen debating citizenship rights: \"Do they serve the koinon?\" (Are they really contributing to the collective fire?)\n\nThe word also implies the dark side—koinon creates pressure to conform, to contribute, to not stand apart. \"That's not koinon\" can be a way to police behavior, to enforce sameness in the name of collective harmony.",
