    {
      "id": "b2cb4c60-ce63-4b05-bc9e-8624b027e228",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**The Kindling**",
      "type": "event",
      "description": "**The Kindling**\n\nThe survivors owe their existence to two things: geography and the Civic Flame.\n\nThe colonies that survived were on defensible terrain — peninsulas, islands, river deltas. Places where beastfolk numbers mattered less and walls could hold. But walls alone would not have saved them.\n\nIn the darkest hour, when every remaining colony was under siege and extinction seemed certain, humans discovered they could pool their SOULs. A single human's magical capacity is weak compared to beastfolk. But hundreds of humans, thousands, all focusing on a single point, believing in a single flame — that is something else entirely.\n\nThe first Flame kindled in desperation. The histories argue over where — Archepyros claims the honor, Antheion insists it was them. What matters is that it worked. The pooled SOUL-energy of an entire city, channeled through a sacred hearth fire, could be released as devastating magical artillery.\n\nThe first time a Flame fired, it vaporized an army.\n\nThe Beasttide broke against walls defended by the Scream — the sound a Flame makes when it unleashes. The beastfolk developed counter-tactics, but the cost was too high, the Flames too deadly. Eventually, other priorities won. The ancestors had been avenged. The sacred lands reclaimed. Let the humans keep their coastal rocks.\n\nA thousand years later, the Thalassic city-states are the descendants of those desperate survivors. Their Civic Flame religion is not philosophy — it is a weapon system that became sacred. And every generation knows, in their bones, that if the Flame ever dies, they will have to face the Beasttide again with nothing.",
