    {
      "id": "707fe957-d6e3-46a7-9a89-e1d802207d5d",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Skaros**",
      "type": "faction",
      "description": "**Skaros**\n\nSkaros occupies the southern coast where the inner sea meets arid lands — a harsh region of salt flats, rocky plateaus, and seasonal oases. The Imperial garrison here was brutal even by colonial standards, and that brutality survived the Rending. When the Beasttide came, Skaros held through sheer viciousness and a Flame that learned to Scream earlier than most.\n\nA warrior-king rules with absolute authority. Succession is theoretically by combat trial, though in practice the previous king usually designates his strongest son and eliminates rivals. The court is austere by Thalassic standards, with displays of wealth considered weakness.\n\nThe Forge Doctrine shapes Skaros philosophy: suffering refines the SOUL. Their warriors deliberately expose themselves to hardship, believing that comfort weakens magic. This channels Passion through endurance rather than emotional intensity, producing disciplined ferocity rather than berserker rage. The doctrine also makes their citizens exceptionally efficient contributors to the Flame — a population hardened by the desert feeds the fire more intensely than soft city-dwellers.\n\nSkaros mercenaries are the most feared on the continent. They fight in disciplined phalanxes that channel collective Passion into devastating charges. Other nations hire them despite finding their culture unsettling.\n\nThe Salt Road gives Skaros economic power beyond their population. They control overland trade routes that bypass Lucian shipping — caravans through the desert carrying goods between the inner sea and points south. The road follows paths that beastfolk caravans walked for millennia before the Empire claimed them.\n\nSkaros and Lucia represent opposite philosophies — martial austerity versus mercantile flexibility — and compete constantly for trade dominance and political influence.\n\n**Population: 4-5 million.** The desert limits density. The capital holds roughly 150,000-200,000.",
