    {
      "id": "56a40c0c-a74f-4c85-9d36-5b7092a00075",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Hintida**",
      "type": "faction",
      "description": "**Hintida**\n\nHintida is the spiritual heart of all beastfolk, not just Tieravel. The populous kingdom occupies a fertile valley considered primordially sacred — possibly where beastfolk first learned to harness the SOUL after the Rending, or perhaps where beastfolk sentience itself first emerged.\n\nThe High Magi rules as both king and high priest. Succession passes through a ritual where the dying magi transfers accumulated knowledge directly into their chosen successor's SOUL. This is dangerous — failed transfers have created mad rulers, and the accumulated knowledge stretches back further than anyone fully understands. A sufficiently skilled High Magi might access memories from before the Rending, from the very origin of beastfolk sentience.\n\nThe Singing Stones are standing stone circles marking power points where the land's memory is concentrated. Hintida has more of these than any other region, and pilgrims come from across Terra — from Zhiran, from Noctria, even secretly from Göran and Drakhar — to touch the places where their ancestors first walked.\n\nHintida is deeply conservative, viewing Noctria's cosmopolitanism as contamination and the human presence as an unhealed wound. The druids argue that trade with humans erodes beastfolk identity, that every compromise brings the First Earth closer to spiritual death. They remember the Beasttide as holy liberation — and they have not forgiven those who stopped the advance before the humans were pushed into the sea entirely.\n\nThe population follows traditional patterns: Satyr nobility and magical leadership, Elaphine administrators and scholars, Lupine warriors, Feline scouts. The Five Natures balance is maintained, but with Satyrs firmly at the apex — this is their homeland more than anyone's, and they have never forgotten it.\n\n**Population: 10-12 million.** The capital holds roughly 200,000-300,000.",
