    {
      "id": "a8f66ef1-66bb-43e1-a887-842b57fca79c",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Noctria**",
      "type": "faction",
      "description": "**Noctria**\n\nNoctria is the most powerful of the beastfolk states, the economic engine of Tieravel. The nation sits at the continent's spine, where the outer reaches meet the inner sea's trade routes. Their capital, New Gloria, began as a trading post where beastfolk and human merchants could meet on neutral ground. It grew into something unprecedented — the second-largest city on Terra, surpassed only by Tonallan itself.\n\nThe government balances a hereditary High Lord against elected guild councils and an advisory druid circle. The balance shifts constantly, with different factions gaining or losing influence based on economic conditions and external threats.\n\nNew Gloria is built on multiple levels climbing a mountainside, a vertical maze of districts. The summit holds the old druid grove, sacred ground that predates the city by millennia. The middle slopes contain merchant quarters, guild halls, and residences. The valley floor handles industry, warehouses, and the constant flow of trade.\n\nThe population is majority Feline and Elaphine, with significant Lupine minorities. Humans are permitted as traders but cannot own property or reside permanently — a compromise that satisfies no one but keeps commerce flowing. Satyrs are rare but influential in the magical academy, which trains mages from across the continent.\n\nNoctria controls the mountain passes connecting the two spheres. Everyone pays tolls. This is the source of their wealth — and their complicated position. They are too mercantile for the traditionalist beastfolk, too beastfolk for the human city-states. Everyone resents them. Everyone needs them.\n\nThe city's success creates tension with its sacred foundations. Every construction project unearths old burial sites. Every expansion disturbs ancestral memory. The druids who advise the High Lord constantly negotiate with the dead, asking permission, making offerings. Some traditionalists argue that New Gloria itself is a desecration — that no city should grow this large on the First Earth. The counter-argument: better a beastfolk city than human colonizers returning.\n\n**Population: 12-14 million.** New Gloria holds roughly 800,000-1,000,000.",
