    {
      "id": "e333ce57-e90b-4d3c-b086-910cba9a100f",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Saltraeth**",
      "type": "faction",
      "description": "**Saltraeth**\n\nThe Saltraeth are the Sea-Clans — beastfolk who took to the water when the Empire pushed them from the land, and never came back.\n\nDuring the Imperial occupation, some beastfolk fled to hidden coves, islands too small to garrison, the sea itself. They became something different. Saltier. Stranger. While their forest cousins remembered the land, the Saltraeth learned to read the tides, to navigate by stars, to strike from the water and vanish before retaliation.\n\nThe Beasttide found them ready. While Hintida sings of warriors storming the walls, the Sea-Clans sing of the night they burned the Imperial fleet. The *Canwr Tân-Môr* (Song of the Sea-Fire) describes how the colonial harbor lit up the sky for three days. They broke the Empire's supply lines. They made the inner sea a grave.\n\nThe Saltraeth are primarily Feline and Lupine — an unusual mix. Felines handle rigging, boarding actions, anything requiring agility. Lupines handle rowing, coordinated maneuvers, pack-tactics in naval combat. The sea teaches cooperation or it teaches drowning.\n\nThey have no kings. A ship is a family. A flotilla is a clan. A tide is a temporary alliance for raiding or war. The Saltmoot gathers clan-leaders for major decisions, rarely.\n\nThe Saltraeth raid Thalassic shipping. This is simply what they do — an ongoing tax that Lucia and Kartheia cannot stop paying. Rules exist: don't sink certain cargoes, don't kill crews who surrender, don't raid during certain seasons. Breaking these rules has consequences within Saltraeth society.\n\nTheir dead rest in the deep water, in the currents, in the salt. The Halwyr (salt-seers) read omens in tides and fish movements. They say the sea remembers everything — every ship it swallowed, every secret whispered on its waves.\n\n**Population: 3-4 million** across coastlines, islands, and ship-communities. Hard to count accurately.",
