    {
      "id": "168e2fd6-858d-4ea9-9b12-6bb13dcf62ac",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Ysgolion**",
      "type": "faction",
      "description": "**Ysgolion**\n\nWhile Hintida prays, Antecentrix fights, and Noctria trades... Ysgolion farms.\n\nSomeone has to.\n\nYsgolion occupies a broad river valley inland — rich soil, gentle hills, reliable rainfall. The kind of land that wants to grow things. The kind of land empires fight over. The Ysgoldir have held this valley since before the Empire came. They held it during occupation (as subjects, as laborers, as the ones who fed Imperial soldiers). They held it after the Beasttide (as the ones who fed beastfolk warriors). They are still holding it.\n\nThe population is predominantly Elaphine — the patient, methodical work of agriculture suits them. Lupine minorities exist in the hillier regions for herding; Felines in the forests at the valley's edges. No Satyrs to speak of. The magical aristocracy never took root here. Ysgolion has farmers, not priests.\n\nVillage councils govern through consensus. Decisions bubble up slowly from village to district to the Cynulliad (the gathering), which meets yearly to decide matters affecting all Ysgolion. There is no king. No High Magi. No war-chief. Hintida finds this baffling. Ysgolion finds Hintida's obsession with hierarchy equally baffling.\n\nYsgolion feeds Hintida (too focused on sacred matters to farm efficiently), Antecentrix (soldiers don't grow food), and Noctria (New Gloria is too large for local supply). This gives them quiet power. They don't threaten. They don't demand. They are simply essential. Everyone knows it. Everyone is polite.\n\nThe resentment is quiet. Patient. But present. Hintida claims spiritual authority — but what has Hintida ever grown? Antecentrix claims to defend all beastfolk — with soldiers fed on Ysgolion bread. Noctria grows rich trading goods Ysgolion produced. Everyone needs Ysgolion. Nobody respects Ysgolion.\n\nThe Cynulliad meetings grow more pointed each year. Nothing has changed yet. But the fields have long memories.\n\n**Population: 7-9 million.** Dense for beastfolk, no major cities. The largest market town holds maybe 30,000-40,000.",
