    {
      "id": "af1f0d69-09b3-4af8-9538-de906a8f8a9c",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**The Marchlands**",
      "type": "location",
      "description": "**The Marchlands**\n\nThe contested middle band where the Thalassic and Brythonic spheres meet. River valleys, coastal hills, and disputed borderlands where no one is safe and everyone is armed.\n\nThis is where the Beasttide broke. The Flames held on the coast; the beastfolk held everything else. The land between became a wound that never healed — too far from the Flames for human settlement, too scarred by a thousand years of skirmishing for beastfolk to reclaim spiritually.\n\nFortress-towns and armed villages dot the landscape. Populations are not mixed so much as *layered* — human territories and beastfolk territories pressed against each other with no buffer, no peace, only exhausted truces. A human farmer knows exactly which hills are safe and which belong to the clans. A beastfolk shepherd knows exactly which rivers mark the Flame-wards.\n\nVarious small lordships and free towns survive by playing both sides — extracting tolls, selling information, hiring out to whoever pays. Independence is precarious. When the great powers go to war, the Marchlands burn first. They always have.\n\nSome ancient records speak of a pact made during the Beasttide — a ceasefire that established this contested zone when the beastfolk advance stalled. If evidence of this pact were found, if it could be proven binding, the political implications would reshape the continent.\n\n**Population: ~5 million.** No major cities. The largest fortified towns hold perhaps 20,000-30,000.",
