    {
      "id": "cd16f714-a919-4184-80a5-c43820d74497",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Contested Narratives**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Contested Narratives**\n\nDifferent groups tell different stories about Tieravel's history and what it means:\n\n**The Hintidan Orthodox View** holds that the humans came as conquerors, enslaved and displaced the beastfolk for centuries, and were rightly driven back during the Beasttide. The liberation was incomplete — the ancestors demand the humans be pushed into the sea entirely. The Flames are an abomination, a perversion of SOUL-magic. One day, they will be extinguished.\n\n**The Noctrian Pragmatist View** holds that the Empire is dead. The Beasttide happened. The humans have their coast; the beastfolk have everything else. Better to trade profitably than to restart a war that burned the continent once. The ancestors want their descendants to *thrive*, not to die avenging thousand-year-old crimes.\n\n**The Human City-State View** holds that whatever the Empire did is not their fault — they are the descendants of survivors, not colonizers. They have lived here a thousand years, built their own civilization, developed their own sacred traditions. The Flames are proof of their right to exist. The beastfolk are welcome to their forests; the coast is human now.\n\n**The Antecentrix Military View** holds that it does not matter who was here first or who did what to whom. What matters is who can hold the land now. The humans hold their coast because their Flames make them too costly to dislodge. The beastfolk hold everything else because the Legions make them too strong to conquer. This is the reality. Strategy must account for it.\n\n**The Ceunant Traditionalist View** holds that the humans are a disease and the land is sick with their presence. The ancestors remember — the Dream-Walkers can show you what the Empire did. One day, they will find a way to quench the Flames. Then the First Earth will finally cleanse itself, and the dead will rest.\n\n**The Ysgolion Pragmatist View** holds that everyone wants to fight, and nobody remembers who grew the grain that fed the warriors. The Beasttide was liberation, yes. It was also exhausting. The fields need tending. The harvest needs bringing in. History is written by those who survive — and survival requires eating.",
