      "id": "4baa0e79-1866-4830-b125-41806c59944f",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**General Practices**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**General Practices**\n\n**Dawn Observances**\n\nThe sun's return is never taken for granted. Common people face east as the sun rises—not formal prayer, just a pause in whatever they're doing. A farmer stops walking to the field. A mother holds her child toward the light for a moment. The gesture is a small, open-palmed lift toward the sun, fingers spread, as if catching warmth. This is called *tonalmaca* (\"giving tonal\") though it's receiving as much as giving—an acknowledgment of the exchange.\n\nThe phrase spoken at dawn varies by region:\n- Yolitzac: *\"Tonatiuh tlachiya\"* — \"The sun sees.\" (Affirmation that dawn happened, that belief held)\n- Yolica: *\"Tlaneci\"* — Simply \"It dawns.\" (Less anxious, more cyclical acceptance)\n- Yullqa: *\"Inti hamun\"* — \"The sun comes.\" (Warmer, more personal—the sun as relative returning)\n\n**Mealtime**\n\nBefore eating, the first bite or first sip is set aside—placed on a small dish, poured on the ground, or simply held up briefly. This \"feeds the age\" in miniature. In wealthy households, this portion goes to a household shrine. In poor households, it goes to the floor or outside the door. The gesture matters more than the destination.\n\nThe phrase is usually just *\"Tonal\"* spoken quietly—acknowledging that what you're about to consume is borrowed heat that will eventually return.\n\n**The Tonal-Touch**\n\nWhen speaking of the dead, when making a serious promise, or when feeling grateful for survival, people touch their chest over the heart with an open palm—where the tonal resides. This is so reflexive that people do it unconsciously while speaking. *\"My mother, tonal rest her\"* [touch]. *\"I swear by my tonal\"* [touch].\n\nA variation: touching the chest and then gesturing upward, palm open, when speaking of someone who died well. This indicates their tonal \"rose\" rather than merely dissipating.\n\n**Common Oaths and Exclamations**\n\n*Frustration/anger:*\n- *\"Yohualli!\"* — \"Darkness!\" (Invoking the enemy—like saying \"damn\")\n- *\"Mictlan take it\"* — Mictlan being the underworld/death realm\n- *\"Moon-cursed\"* — Adjective for something that keeps going wrong\n\n*Surprise:*\n- *\"Tonal!\"* — Like \"God!\" or \"Christ!\"—the sacred word as exclamation\n- *\"Tonatiuh's eye!\"* — \"Sun's eye!\" (Stronger, used for genuine shock)\n\n*Emphasis/swearing truth:*\n- *\"By my tonal\"* — Swearing on your life-heat; serious oath\n- *\"The sun sees\"* — Equivalent to \"God as my witness\"\n- *\"May my tonal rise\"* — \"May I die well if I'm lying\"\n\n*Relief:*\n- *\"The sun holds\"* — Everything's okay; the crisis passed\n- *\"Still warm\"* — More casual version; \"we're still alive\"",
