      "id": "989413cc-b0e6-446c-97ab-67398dd1299b",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Yolitzac (Imperial Core)**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Yolitzac (Imperial Core)**\n\nYolitzac is where the dualist theology is strongest—the eternal struggle between sun and moon, the belief that collective faith literally sustains the dawn. This creates a culture with an undercurrent of anxiety that other Yolcentla regions find exhausting.\n\n**Dawn Anxiety**\n\nIn Yolitzac, dawn isn't just acknowledged—it's *watched for*. The final hours of night carry genuine tension, especially in devout households.\n\nThe tradition of keeping someone awake through the pre-dawn hours is taken seriously here. In common households, family members rotate this duty. In wealthy households, servants handle it. The watcher keeps a small fire burning and faces east, alert for the first light. When the sun appears, they call out—*\"Tlanextia!\"* (\"It brightens!\")—and the household stirs.\n\nThe phrase that follows sunrise is *\"Tonatiuh tlachiya\"*—\"The sun sees.\" This is said with genuine relief. The night is over. Belief held. The enemy moon has retreated again.\n\nPeople who sleep through dawn without anyone watching are considered careless at best, faithless at worst. Visitors from other regions find this bewildering—surely the sun will rise whether you watch or not? Yolitzac natives find *that* attitude bewildering. *Of course* the sun rises because people believe it will. That's how it works.\n\n**Lunar Vigilance**\n\nThe moon is the defeated enemy who keeps returning. Full moons are nights of mild unease; lunar eclipses are spiritual crises.\n\nDuring a lunar eclipse, Yolitzac essentially shuts down. People gather in temples and public squares, drums beat continuously, and priests lead chanting designed to \"strengthen\" the sun. The fear is real: what if this time the moon wins? What if the sun doesn't come back?\n\nEven in daily life, references to the moon are mildly taboo. Calling something \"moon-touched\" or \"lunar\" implies it's cursed, unstable, or treasonous. The moon appears on no decorations, no art, no clothing. To paint the moon is to honor the enemy.\n\nPeople avoid looking directly at the moon when it's visible. Glancing is fine; staring is uncomfortable. Doing anything *by moonlight* that could be done by firelight or waited for dawn is vaguely improper.\n\n**Confession of Doubts**\n\nYolitzac theology holds that doubt weakens the collective faith that sustains the sun. This creates a practice somewhere between religious confession and mental hygiene: regular unburdening of doubts to priests.\n\nCommon people visit temple for this monthly or when troubled. The priest listens, offers reassurance, and performs a small ritual to \"release\" the doubt—often involving breathing over a flame, letting the fire consume the weakness. The goal isn't punishment but *relief*. You've had dark thoughts; that's human. Now let them go so they don't fester and spread.\n\nThis makes Yolitzac culture uncomfortable with unexpressed negativity. Doubts, fears, despair—these should be spoken and released, not harbored. Someone who seems troubled but won't talk about it is spiritually dangerous. They're hoarding darkness.\n\n**Yolitzac Oaths and Exclamations**\n\n*Frustration/anger:*\n- *\"Yohualli!\"* — \"Darkness!\" The basic curse\n- *\"Moon take it\"* — Stronger; consigning something to the enemy\n- *\"Eclipse-cursed\"* — Something that keeps failing; the worst luck\n- *\"Mictlan's teeth\"* — Invoking the death realm; crude but common\n\n*Surprise:*\n- *\"Tonatiuh!\"* — \"Sun!\" The basic exclamation\n- *\"Light of heaven!\"* — Stronger surprise\n- *\"The sun sees!\"* — Can be surprise or emphasis\n\n*Fear/unease:*\n- *\"The moon watches\"* — Something feels wrong; bad omen\n- *\"Dark hours\"* — A dangerous or uncertain time\n- *\"Fading light\"* — Things are getting worse\n\n*Emphasis/swearing truth:*\n- *\"By the sun's eye\"* — Standard oath\n- *\"May I face the dark\"* — Serious oath; if I lie, let me face the moon's victory\n- *\"The Tonalpouhqui hears\"* — Invoking the religious authority; very formal\n- *\"On my tonal, before the light\"* — Strongest oath; combining personal and cosmic stakes\n\n*Relief:*\n- *\"The sun holds\"* — Crisis passed; the light endures\n- *\"Dawn comes\"* — Reassurance; this darkness is temporary\n- *\"Still bright\"* — We're okay; the faith holds\n\n*Contempt:*\n- *\"Moon-gazer\"* — Someone suspected of disloyalty or heresy\n- *\"Night-lover\"* — Stronger insult; someone who embraces darkness\n- *\"Doubter\"* — Serious accusation; someone whose weakness endangers everyone\n\n**Yolitzac Gestures**\n\nThe *tonal-touch* (palm to chest) is universal across Yolcentla, but Yolitzac adds a specific gesture for dawn: palm open, fingers spread, lifted toward the rising sun. This is done automatically upon seeing sunrise, often accompanied by *\"Tonatiuh tlachiya.\"*\n\nWhen speaking of the moon or darkness or anything ill-omened, a quick gesture of *aversion*—hand flicked outward, palm out, as if pushing something away. This is reflexive; people do it while speaking without noticing.\n\nWhen entering a temple or passing a significant shrine, Yolitzac people touch their eyes and then gesture toward the flame—*the fire that helps me see, that keeps the darkness back.*",
