    {
      "id": "65dbfb20-56bc-4fd8-a398-8904b8f7c1df",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Micteca (Place of the Dead)**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Micteca (Place of the Dead)**\n\nBuilt around a massive Primordial access point—likely a vast cave system—Micteca specializes in death. Other kingdoms find them unsettling; everyone needs them.\n\n**Death as Profession**\n\nMicteca priests are specialists in dying well. Important people from across Yolcentla send their dying to Micteca, or summon Micteca priests to attend final moments. The work involves preparing the dying person's tonal for its journey, negotiating with ancestors who will receive them, and ensuring the death \"takes\" properly so the soul doesn't linger or wander.\n\nThis makes Micteca culture unusually comfortable with mortality. Where others avoid death-talk, Micteca people discuss it plainly. This isn't morbidity—it's professional competence. A Micteca native might calmly assess how someone will probably die and what preparations would be advisable, then be baffled when others find this conversation uncomfortable.\n\n**The Living and the Dead**\n\nThe caves beneath Micteca are where the Primordial runs close enough to touch. Priests descend to commune with the accumulated dead, carry messages, seek advice. Coming back up is not guaranteed—some priests stay too long and return strange, or don't return at all.\n\nCommon people don't enter the deep caves, but they live in proximity to the dead in ways others don't. Ancestor consultation is casual and frequent. Before major decisions, a Micteca native might visit a cave-mouth shrine to \"ask the family\"—not a formal séance, just a quiet conversation with those below.\n\n**Micteca Oaths and Exclamations**\n\n- *\"Mictlan's breath\"* — Basic exclamation (the underworld breathes out from the caves)\n- *\"Bones and shadow\"* — Stronger emphasis\n- *\"The dead know\"* — Affirmation of truth; you can't lie to those below\n- *\"By those who wait\"* — Oath invoking ancestors\n- *\"May I wander\"* — Serious oath; the worst fate is a soul that can't find rest\n- *\"Good journey\"* — Farewell, especially to the dying but also general use\n- *\"The caves remember\"* — Warning; secrets don't stay secret\n\n**Micteca Gestures**\n\nWhen speaking of the dead, Micteca people gesture *downward*—the opposite of most Yolcentla cultures. The dead are below, in the caves, in the earth. A downward palm-press acknowledges them.\n\nWhen passing cave-mouths or shrines to the dead, a pause and slight bow—not fearful, but respectful. You're at a threshold. Those on the other side are watching.\n\nMicteca greetings often include a phrase outsiders find morbid: *\"Still walking?\"* The answer is *\"Still walking.\"* It's not pessimism—it's acknowledgment of the obvious. Everyone dies. We're still here today. That's worth noting.",
