    {
      "id": "a0a9a13c-e1db-4343-879f-7c9abecc31cd",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Oliken (The City-States)**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Oliken (The City-States)**\n\nThe southern lowlands are fragmented into rival city-states sharing cultural roots but competing constantly. The Hero Twins prophecy is central: two figures who will descend to the Primordial and outwit death itself.\n\n**Prophetic Competition**\n\nEach major city claims the Hero Twins will emerge from *their* sacred sites. This isn't abstract theology—it's civic identity and political legitimacy. If your city produces the Twins, you rule Oliken. Maybe all of Yolcentla.\n\nThis creates cities obsessed with signs, omens, exceptional children, and prophetic interpretation. Any unusual birth (twins especially, but also strange circumstances, exceptional beauty, or unusual markings) gets examined by priests. Most are dismissed. Some are watched. Very rarely, someone is declared a candidate.\n\nThe pressure on these candidates is immense. Most fail to demonstrate the necessary qualities and are quietly retired from consideration. A few go mad. The very rare success—a candidate who demonstrates genuine supernatural ability—becomes a political earthquake.\n\n**Cenote Veneration**\n\nThe cenotes (natural sinkholes filled with water) are sacred access points to the Primordial. The cities are built around them. Pilgrims come to make offerings, seek visions, and sometimes to sacrifice.\n\nWater from cenotes is holy. Wealthy households import it for important rituals. Bathing in cenote water is purifying. Drowning in a cenote—accidental or sacrificial—is a particularly powerful death, the tonal going directly into the Primordial rather than rising to the sun.\n\n**Oliken Oaths and Exclamations**\n\n- *\"Twins witness!\"* — Basic oath; invoking the awaited heroes\n- *\"Cenote-deep\"* — Something profound, serious, or hidden\n- *\"By the water below\"* — Stronger oath; the sacred pools\n- *\"Death-outwitters\"* — Praise for someone clever; invoking the Twins' legendary cunning\n- *\"May the Twins pass me by\"* — Oath with a twist; if I lie, let me not be chosen (being a Twin candidate is an honor but also a burden)\n- *\"Which city?\"* — Challenge; \"who do you think you are?\" (everyone's civic pride is tender)\n- *\"Ball-court rules\"* — A situation where the stakes are absolute; in the mythic ball game, losers die\n\n**Oliken Gestures**\n\nWhen making serious oaths, Oliken people often cup their hands as if holding water—the cenote, the sacred pool, the access to the Primordial.\n\nWhen speaking of the Twins (the prophecy, not actual twins), a gesture of two fingers raised—index and middle finger together. This is also a sign of hope, used when encouraging someone facing long odds.\n\nCivic pride is touchy. When an Oliken native names their home city, there's often a small unconscious gesture of emphasis—a hand to heart, a slight lift of the chin. Insulting someone's city is fighting words.",
