    {
      "id": "31041d17-79b0-4ed9-8edc-c47bba7f5a48",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Chalatica (The Sea-Mouths Republic)**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Chalatica (The Sea-Mouths Republic)**\n\nA confederation of port cities governed by merchant families. Religious practice is more transactional than elsewhere—offerings made for specific purposes, results expected. The gods (or the sun, or the sea, or the ancestors) are trading partners, not masters.\n\n**Maritime Religion**\n\nThe sea is the second power here—not opposed to the sun but parallel to it. Fishers and sailors make offerings to both: to the sun for light and warmth, to the sea for fish and safe passage. Neither is neglected; both can kill you.\n\nSea-offerings happen at the water's edge. Before launching, sailors pour a small amount of alcohol into the waves. Returning safely, they pour more. The sea is thanked but not trusted—\"the sea is hungry\" is a common saying, acknowledging that the water takes as much as it gives.\n\n**Syncretic Tolerance**\n\nChalatica ports host beastfolk traders, and their religious practices have leaked in around the edges. Some Chalatica families have adopted ancestor practices that look suspiciously like beastfolk gwraidd-veneration. Orthodox priests disapprove. Merchants shrug. Whatever works.\n\nThis makes Chalatica people religiously flexible in ways that shock inland visitors. A Chalatica merchant might participate in a beastfolk offering ritual for business reasons and see nothing wrong with it. \"All roads reach the same harbor,\" they say—a phrase that would be heresy in Yolitzac.\n\n**Chalatica Oaths and Exclamations**\n\n- *\"Sun and sea!\"* — Basic exclamation; covering both powers\n- *\"Salt take it\"* — Frustration; the sea as devourer\n- *\"Good wind\"* — Approval; favorable conditions\n- *\"By the harbor\"* — Oath invoking home port; for Chalatica, where you dock matters more than which god you invoke\n- *\"All roads reach\"* — Acceptance; there's more than one way\n- *\"The tide knows\"* — The sea reveals truth; secrets wash up eventually\n- *\"Dryfoot\"* — Mild insult; someone who doesn't understand the sea (and therefore the world)\n\n**Chalatica Gestures**\n\nWhen speaking of luck, fortune, or hope, Chalatica people make a small wave-motion with one hand—the unpredictable sea that might favor you.\n\nWhen entering into agreements, the merchant gesture is an open hand extended, then turned palm-up—*showing you have nothing hidden, inviting inspection.* This has become a general Chalatica greeting among social equals.\n\nWhen speaking of the dead, the gesture depends on how they died. Died at sea: wave-motion, looking toward the water. Died on land: the standard tonal-touch and upward gesture. The sea keeps its dead differently than the sun does.",
