    {
      "id": "fb18500f-835a-4221-8377-14b78faff6d3",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Morning and Evening**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Morning and Evening**\n\nThe day begins and ends with stillness. Orthodox households practice *jìngzuò* (\"quiet sitting\")—a few minutes of silent, settled breathing. This isn't meditation in a mystical sense; it's finding your shùn for the day, settling into the current before you start swimming.\n\nThe very devout do this facing a household shrine that typically contains: an image or character representing Heaven, a small dish of water representing the River, and tablets or images for ancestors. Incense optional, more common in southern regions.\n\nEvening *jìngzuò* is about releasing the day—letting go of frustrations, disappointments, struggles. *Don't carry nì (resistance) into sleep.*\n\nCommon people often skip formal sitting but still have a moment of quiet before starting work. A farmer pauses at the field's edge. A merchant pauses before opening shop. A bureaucrat pauses before picking up the first document. The principle matters more than the form.",
