    {
      "id": "4088ea2e-0a8a-4ce8-8ea8-450564d12b0c",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Zhiran Gestures**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Zhiran Gestures**\n\nThe *flow-hand*: when speaking of acceptance, of letting go, of proper order, Zhiran people make a small flowing gesture with one hand—fingers together, a gentle wave moving away from the body, like water flowing downstream. This accompanies phrases like \"shùn, then\" or \"the river knows.\"\n\nWhen showing respect to elders or superiors, a small bow with hands clasped in front. The depth of bow indicates relative status. Getting this wrong is embarrassing but forgivable for foreigners.\n\nWhen passing a temple or shrine, a brief pause and nod. Not full obeisance—just acknowledgment. Rushing past without acknowledging is rude, suggesting you think you're too important for propriety.",
