      "name": "**Movement as Devotion**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Movement as Devotion**\n\nThe Lupines of Göran have no temples because temples are settled. Their observances happen in motion.\n\nThe morning begins with *stretching toward the wind*—facing whatever direction the wind blows from, stretching arms wide, and taking deep breaths. This is done naked when possible, or at least with the chest exposed. You greet the khuur with your body before anything else. Children learn this before they learn to ride.\n\nBefore a journey, a rider pauses to feel the wind direction, then speaks to it: *\"Khuur, run with me\"* or *\"Khuur, guide my path.\"* This isn't optional politeness—leaving without acknowledging the wind is like ignoring a host in their own home.",
