    {
      "id": "c811bdf7-1e44-4d6d-841f-a1685c877fa3",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Meals**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Meals**\n\nBefore eating meat (and almost everything is meat), a small portion is thrown to the wind—tossed in the air rather than placed down. *What falls to earth isn't the offering. What the wind catches is.* Children sometimes try to see how far their portion goes; this is tolerated as good instinct.\n\nBefore drinking *airag* (fermented mare's milk), a finger is dipped in and flicked toward the sky—drops for the khuur, drops for the ancestors riding it.\n\nEating in complete stillness is uncomfortable. Meals should happen around fires, with wind, with movement nearby—horses shifting, children running, dogs circling. A still, silent meal feels like death.",
