      "id": "b1fe71fe-2dec-4304-9df8-c5bf96f457c8",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Göran Gestures**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Göran Gestures**\n\nThe *wind-catch*: when speaking of the dead, of freedom, of important journeys, Lupines raise one hand and make a catching motion in the air—like grabbing at something blowing past. This indicates connection to the khuur, to the eternal.\n\nWhen meeting someone after long absence, the greeting involves clasping forearms (not hands) and a brief pressing of foreheads together. This mingles breath—sharing the wind you've been breathing.\n\nWhen a decision is made, a Lupine might turn their head to feel the wind direction, then nod. *Checking with the khuur.* Even if there's no perceptible wind, the gesture matters.",
