      "name": "**Flame Acknowledgment**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Flame Acknowledgment**\n\nThe Civic Flame isn't metaphor—it's a literal fire burning in the city's central hearth. Citizens interact with it directly and indirectly throughout daily life.\n\nEvery citizen household maintains a *small flame*—an oil lamp or candle that is theoretically lit from the central Flame and never allowed to die. In practice, flames do go out and are quietly relit, but households are embarrassed about it. The home flame is kept in a prominent place, often by the entrance.\n\nWhen leaving the house, many citizens pause briefly at their home flame, touching the lamp or holder. *Carrying the koinon with you.* When returning, the same gesture—*bringing yourself back to the collective.*\n\nStreet shrines and small public flames dot the city at intersections, market squares, and gates. Passing citizens make a small gesture—touching fingers to lips then extending toward the flame, or a brief palm-out acknowledgment. Not every time, but regularly. Rushing past without acknowledgment, especially at major shrines, is noticed.",
