    {
      "id": "2bf2a532-3a84-49d1-bc51-2af7a6f60a22",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Morning Practice**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Morning Practice**\n\nGoryun people—especially those with any martial training, which is culturally encouraged—begin the day with physical practice. This might be formal martial forms, simple stretching, a walk, or farm labor that doubles as exercise. The principle is that the body should *move* before the mind engages serious work.\n\nThis isn't ritualized the way Zhiran's quiet-sitting is. There's no specific prayer or posture. It's more of a cultural expectation: you don't sit down to important business with a cold body. The Hwarang formalized this into elaborate dawn training, but common people just... move first.\n\nTea follows morning movement. Goryun adopted tea culture from Zhiran but drinks it differently—less ceremony, more function. A cup of hot tea after exertion, feeling the warmth settle while your breathing slows. The moment where fire meets stillness. This is dallyeom in miniature, though nobody calls it that out loud.",
