    {
      "id": "e4d78211-f818-49d6-80da-a473b043923a",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Emotional Expression**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Emotional Expression**\n\nHere's where Jeongyeol philosophy actually shows up in daily life: Goryun people are allowed to *feel* things visibly in ways that Zhiran finds unseemly.\n\nAnger, joy, grief, passion—these aren't suppressed. But they're *held*. A Goryun person might weep openly at a funeral, but they don't collapse. They might laugh loudly at a joke, but they don't lose themselves in hilarity. The goal is to feel fully while remaining *yourself*—the container holding the fire, not the fire escaping the container.\n\nThis is dallyeom in practice, though people don't use the philosophical term in everyday speech. They might say someone \"held well\" at a difficult moment, or \"kept their center,\" or \"didn't let it master them.\" Conversely, someone who suppresses emotion entirely is \"cold\" or \"closed\"—equally a failure, just in the other direction.",
