    {
      "id": "5146d680-460c-43eb-991a-a661ba2d6dff",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Goryun Gestures**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Goryun Gestures**\n\nThe *three-tap*—three quick taps on a table, wall, or your own chest—invokes the Three Fires. Used for emphasis, for oaths, for moments of national pride. Before drinking a toast, you might tap three times on the table.\n\nWhen steadying yourself or someone else, a hand on the shoulder with a firm grip—not a pat, but a grounding pressure. *Helping them hold.* This is done between equals or from elder to younger; doing it to a superior would be presumptuous.\n\nWhen greeting someone after they've been through hardship, you clasp their forearm and *look at them*—a searching look. *Checking that they came through whole, that the fire's still there.* The appropriate response is to meet the gaze steadily.\n\nThe formal Hwarang salute—right fist to left chest, over the heart—has filtered into civilian life for serious moments. It's not used casually, but at ceremonies, before duels, when making serious commitments.",
