      "name": "**Display as Devotion**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Display as Devotion**\n\nThe Pavonines value visibility, authenticity, showing your true self. Their observances are almost opposite to cultures that value restraint.\n\nMorning begins with *grooming*—specifically, with attention to feathers. This isn't vanity; it's spiritual practice. Your plumage is your kagami made visible. Neglecting it is neglecting your divine display. Even the poorest Pavonine takes time each morning to arrange and clean their feathers.\n\nWhen something significant happens—good news, bad news, important visitors—Pavonines often *display*. Males raise and fan their tail feathers; females have subtler displays involving wing-angles and crest-raising. This isn't showing off; it's *responding authentically.* Suppressing the display in significant moments is considered spiritually unhealthy.",
