      "id": "adfbe284-db76-4bec-8ee3-8b96d3898334",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**Aohane Gestures**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Aohane Gestures**\n\nPavonines communicate enormously through feather-position, which mammals can't fully read. But some gestures are obvious:\n\nThe *display-bow*—a brief spreading of wings and/or tail in greeting. The extent indicates respect; a full display to a superior, a minimal acknowledgment to an equal.\n\nWhen being sincere, Pavonines often angle themselves to catch better light, or turn to show their profile. *Presenting their kagami clearly.* Turning away from light or presenting your back during serious conversation is rude.\n\nWhen speaking of the dead, Pavonines look *up* and often make a small wing-flutter—the kagami returning to heaven, the display complete.",
