      "name": "**Aohane Humans**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**Aohane Humans**\n\nA small human population exists in Aohane's port towns—traders, diplomatic staff, and families who have lived there for generations. They occupy an odd position: tolerated, sometimes valued, but never fully part of Pavonine society. They cannot display. They have no plumage. Their kagami, if they have one, is invisible.\n\n**Adapted Practices**\n\nAohane humans have developed their own version of kagami-practice, focused on what they *can* show: clothing, bearing, expression, voice.\n\nMorning grooming matters here more than anywhere else humans live. An Aohane human takes care with their appearance—not Pavonine-style feather-arrangement, but careful attention to clothing, hair, cleanliness. To appear disheveled is to show disrespect for the principle of display, even if you can't display like a Pavonine.\n\nColor in clothing carries weight. Aohane humans wear brighter colors than humans elsewhere typically would—not garish, but *visible*. Dressing in dull browns and grays reads as hiding yourself, as failed kagami. The wealthy compete in fabric quality and dye richness; the poor at least keep their clothes clean and mended.\n\n**The Voice as Display**\n\nSince humans can't communicate through feather-position, Aohane humans have developed unusual attention to vocal expression. Tone, clarity, musicality—these become the human equivalent of plumage.\n\nSpeaking in a flat monotone is considered as rude as a Pavonine hiding their crest. Aohane humans learn to *perform* their speech: clear articulation, expressive tone, appropriate volume. Mumbling is shameful. Children are trained in vocal exercises the way Pavonine children are trained in display-postures.\n\nThis makes Aohane humans distinctive when they travel. Other humans find them theatrical, overly expressive, \"always performing.\" They find other humans muffled, hidden, spiritually closed.\n\n**Religious Syncretism**\n\nMost Aohane humans have adopted kagami-theology at least partially. They speak of \"showing truly\" and \"false colors\" and accept the basic premise that authenticity is virtue. But they've adapted it to human limitations.\n\nSome have developed a theology of *inner kagami*—the idea that humans display through actions and words rather than plumage, that their soul shines through behavior rather than feathers. This is heterodox from a Pavonine perspective (kagami should be *visible*), but it's tolerated as a reasonable human adaptation.\n\nOthers maintain their ancestral faiths privately while performing kagami-observance publicly. A human family might keep a small shrine to Zhiran-style ancestors or Yolcentla-style sun-worship in their home, then step outside and greet neighbors with \"Bright kagami!\" This dual practice is common and unremarked.\n\n**Aohane Human Oaths and Exclamations**\n\nAohane humans use many Pavonine expressions but have developed their own variants:\n\n- *\"Bright kagami!\"* — Adopted directly; standard greeting\n- *\"By my voice\"* — Human adaptation; swearing on their form of display\n- *\"True-spoken\"* — Equivalent to \"true colors\" but for verbal honesty\n- *\"May my words dull\"* — Oath; let my voice lose its clarity if I lie\n- *\"Cloth and color!\"* — Surprise; invoking their form of display\n- *\"Dressed dark\"* — Criticism; someone hiding, not showing themselves\n- *\"Good showing\"* — Praise; someone presenting themselves well\n\n**Aohane Human Gestures**\n\nWithout feathers to manipulate, Aohane humans have developed substitute gestures:\n\nThe *color-touch*—briefly touching your own clothing when speaking of honesty or identity. Where a Pavonine might fan their tail, a human touches their bright sleeve. *This is what I show. This is my kagami.*\n\nThe *open-hand greeting*—palms up, arms slightly spread, showing you have nothing hidden. This has become the standard human greeting in Aohane, replacing bows or handshakes.\n\nWhen speaking of the dead, Aohane humans look up like Pavonines do, but instead of a wing-flutter, they make a small gesture with both hands—fingers spreading upward like something rising and dispersing. *The display complete. The kagami returning.*\n\n**Tensions**\n\nAohane humans live with a quiet awareness that they can never fully belong. No matter how bright their clothes, how musical their voice, how sincere their kagami-practice—they cannot *display*. They are spiritually limited in Pavonine eyes, doing their best with what they have.\n\nSome Aohane humans resent this. A few have left for places where their humanity isn't a spiritual handicap. But many have made peace with it, finding dignity in their adapted practices, taking pride in being the best-dressed, clearest-voiced humans in the world.\n\nPavonines generally view Aohane humans with something between condescension and genuine respect. *They try. They cannot help what they are. And their voice-displays are genuinely impressive, for mammals.*",
