    {
      "id": "33e2fce7-5b47-4de8-b56f-c65485fe640e",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**What the Flames Believe About Each Other**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**What the Flames Believe About Each Other**\n\n**\"Lucia has sold out to the beasts.\"** The other Thalassic states view Lucia's tolerance for beastfolk trade as moral compromise. They ignore that Lucia's pragmatism has made it the wealthiest human state on the continent.\n\n**\"Skaros are barely civilized.\"** The austerity of the Forge Doctrine looks like barbarism to softer Thalassic cities. They underestimate both the discipline and the genuine spiritual philosophy behind Skaros practice.\n\n**\"Kartheia will provoke a war.\"** Everyone worries about Kartheian expansion into the Marchlands. The worry is justified, but often overstated—Kartheian assemblies are cautious about risking their young Flames.\n\n**\"Antheion thinks it rules us.\"** Resentment of Antheion's age, wealth, and prestige is widespread. The Philosopher-Kings' claims to wisdom are mocked privately, even as their grain feeds the other cities.\n\n**\"The Syndikaia are cowards.\"** The five-city alliance is criticized for refusing to take sides in Thalassic politics. The critics ignore that the Syndikaia's neutrality has kept them alive for a thousand years.\n\n**\"Archepyros secretly pulls strings.\"** The Sacred Isle's role as spiritual arbiter makes it suspect. Every political outcome is sometimes attributed to hidden Pyrarch influence. In reality, Archepyros is far less powerful than this gives them credit for.",
