    {
      "id": "be064b0f-5556-4bb4-b37a-53c694c9879b",
      "storyId": "55fed642-2517-4046-865d-17e3ade46d48",
      "name": "**What Brythonic Nations Believe About Each Other**",
      "type": "concept",
      "description": "**What Brythonic Nations Believe About Each Other**\n\n**\"Hintida claims authority it hasn't earned.\"** Antecentrix, Noctria, and Ysgolion all resent Hintida's claim to spiritual leadership. The High Magi presides over rituals, but his political influence is often exaggerated—or resisted.\n\n**\"Noctria has sold out to trade.\"** The traditionalist critique: New Gloria's wealth comes from compromising beastfolk values, trading with humans, prioritizing profit over purity. Noctrians counter that someone has to keep the economy functional.\n\n**\"Antecentrix has become what it fights.\"** Hintida's critique: the Legions use Imperial tactics, Imperial organization, Imperial thinking. They have absorbed the enemy. Antecentrix counters that defeating humans requires understanding human methods.\n\n**\"Ysgolion are just farmers.\"** The widespread dismissal of the agricultural nation ignores their quiet power. Everyone needs Ysgolion grain. No one respects Ysgolion for providing it.\n\n**\"Ceunant are mad.\"** The Dream-Walkers' practices make other beastfolk uneasy. Spending too long in ancestral memory can blur your sense of self. Ceunant's withdrawn isolationism looks like instability from outside.\n\n**\"The Saltraeth aren't really one of us.\"** The Sea-Clans are too strange, too changed by their maritime existence. Land-based beastfolk sometimes forget they fought the same liberation war.",
